the light of this case of a failure to return from temporary release from open prison, which led to a further offence. Keeping the public safe is our priority and we will not allow the actions of a small minority of offenders to undermine public confidence in the prison system. The number of temporary release failures remains very low; less that one failure in every 1,000 releases and about five in every 100,000 releases involving alleged offending, but we take each and every incident seriously. The Government has already ordered immediate changes to tighten up the system as a matter of urgency. With immediate effect, prisoners will no longer be transferred to open conditions if they have previously absconded from open prisons; or if they have failed to return or reoffended whilst released on temporary licence.</p><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2014-06-16T17:15:39.9160416Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/60853/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/60853/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/60853/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-09","Michael Wheatley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether approval was sought from Ministers for the decision to move Michael Wheatley to an open prison.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","199681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/60854","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-06-16","<p>Approval was not sought from any Minister for the decision to release Michael Wheatley on temporary licence, as the policy does not require Ministerial approval before a prisoner is approved for release on temporary licence (RoTL). This has been the case since 1994. In accordance with the policy, as laid down in Prison Service Order 6300, the Deputy Governor at HMP Standford Hill approved RoTL for Michael Wheatley, on a recommendation from a RoTL risk assessment board at that prison.</p><p> </p><p>Mr Wheatley's Resettlement Day Release was authorised to facilitate his potential resettlement into the community and to assess his ongoing risk, to inform the Parole Board's future decision as to his suitability for release into the community on life licence.</p><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright","199683","2014-06-16T14:49:23.3659979Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/60854/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/60854/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/60854/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-06-09","Michael Wheatley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether approval was sought from any Minister for the decision to release Michael Wheatley on temporary licence.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","199682"
