"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61084","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-06-12","<p> </p><p>Ofwat is assessing water infrastructure investment plans for 2015-2020 under the 2014 water price review. All water and sewerage companies have a duty derived from recent legislation to place greater emphasis on flood risk planning.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The Water Industry Act 1991 has also been amended to make clear that sewerage undertakers can construct and use Sustainable Drainage Systems to fulfil their statutory duty to effectually drain an area where it is the most economical solution.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-06-12T14:13:41.3813217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61084/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61084/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61084/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-06-09","Flood Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of water infrastructure investment plans in tackling the problem of flooding; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Charlie Elphicke","Dover","Charlie Elphicke","904181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61315","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-06-12","<p> </p><p>Stimulating economic growth in rural areas is a key priority for Defra and I recognise the importance of the food and drink sector to the rural economy.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Rural Development Programme is now and will continue to support food and drink producers in rural areas to deliver growth and create jobs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In addition, we are helping local food businesses gain recognition for protected food names. Over 60 British foods are now recognised in this way, including Herefordshire Cider and Perry.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-06-12T16:41:47.1439698Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61315/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61315/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61315/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-06-09","Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he is taking to help rural food and drink producers.","false","Biography information for Jesse Norman","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","904183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61372","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-06-12","<p> </p><p>We will almost double the direct payment rate in the moorland from 2015. We will also equalise the payment rates in the Severely Disadvantaged Area and the lowland. Taken together, these changes will distribute direct payments more equitably across English farms. They will also ensure that upland farmers on large areas of moorland are not put at a disadvantage in comparison with other upland farmers.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-06-12T16:40:43.7409772Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61372/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61372/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61372/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-06-09","Hill Farming","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to support moorland farmers.","false","Biography information for Mel Stride","Central Devon","Mel Stride","904182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61518","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-06-12","<p> </p><p>The success of the bovine TB eradication policies pursued in countries such as Australia, New Zealand, the United States, the Republic of Ireland and France demonstrates the need to bear down on the disease effectively in both cattle and in wildlife.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There is no single solution.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-06-12T16:38:51.3366221Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61518/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61518/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61518/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-06-09","Bovine Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of progress in other countries on tackling bovine TB in cattle and wildlife.","false","Biography information for Glyn Davies","Montgomeryshire","Glyn Davies","904180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61519","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-06-12","<p> </p><p>As part of the Red Tape Challenge Agriculture theme, we announced in January the Government's intention to scrap 156 regulations and improve 134 others. There were 11 reform proposals related to equine regulation in Defra's Agriculture theme. An implementation plan containing these proposals was contained in Defra's “Better for Business – Strategic Reform Plan” published on 09 April 2014 which is available publicly, online.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2014-06-12T16:42:59.3561375Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61519/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61519/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61519/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-06-09","Horses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the burden of regulation on the equine industry in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr David Ruffley","Bury St Edmunds","Mr David Ruffley","904186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61520","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-06-12","<p> </p><p>During this financial year the Environment Agency will invest £380,000 in maintaining flood defences and structures on the Severn Estuary in Gloucestershire. An additional £2 million will be invested to repair flood defences and structures damaged during the winter floods.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Severn Estuary Flood Risk Management Strategy identified a need for around £58 million of funding in Gloucestershire over the next 100 years to maintain or improve flood defences in the Estuary.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-06-12T15:48:15.501505Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61520/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61520/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61520/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-06-09","Flood Control: Severn Estuary","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he is taking to improve and maintain flood defences along the Severn Estuary.","false","Biography information for Neil Carmichael","Stroud","Neil Carmichael","904187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61521","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2014-06-12","<p> </p><p>Defra spent £8.3 million in 2013-14 under its core adapting to climate change programme. This included £4.1 million to the Met Office Hadley Centre for the provision of world-leading climate science, and £1.6 million to the Environment Agency's Climate Ready support service to help organisations across England adapt to a changing climate. Adaptation is mainstreamed across Government. Other departments and other Defra programmes also fund activities that build resilience to climate change.</p><p> </p>","North Cornwall","Dan Rogerson",,"2014-06-12T14:23:45.2627311Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61521/answer","Biography information for Dan Rogerson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61521/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/61521/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2014-06-09","Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what level of funding his Department provides to tackle the effects of climate change; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Graeme Morrice","Livingston","Graeme Morrice","904184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/60430","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-11","<p>The £8 per tonne escalator in the standard rate of landfill tax has been extremely successful in reducing waste sent to landfill and providing certainty to the industry to invest in alternative technologies which help to ensure a more sustainable use of resources. Budget 2014 provided further certainty on the future of both the standard and lower rates by confirming that they will not be eroded by inflation in future years.</p><p> </p><p>Budget 2014 also announced an additional £5m of funding to tackle waste crime, which will assist in the Environment Agency's drive to ensure effective compliance and enforcement with waste legislation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Loughborough","Nicky Morgan",,"2014-06-11T15:54:40.6818051Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/60430/answer","Biography information for Nicky Morgan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/60430/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/60430/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-06","Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what fiscal steps he has taken to promote the circular economy and sustainable use of resources.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","199547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/60431","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-06-16","<p>Over the last year, we have received reports of human rights violations in Western Sahara from a number of sources including the Moroccan National Human Rights Council, UN Special Rapporteurs, international human rights organisations and civil society groups. However, none of these have released information on the number of violations.</p>","Faversham and Mid Kent","Hugh Robertson","199477","2014-06-16T09:49:25.9046699Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/60431/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugh Robertson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/60431/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/60431/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-06-06","Morocco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how the number of allegations of human rights violations perpetrated by the Moroccan Security Forces against Saharawi citizens has been monitored (a) since Resolution 2099 was passed on 25 April 2013 and (b) since Resolution 2152 was passed on 25 April 2014.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","199457"
